<scenario>
The agent A provided the following violation scenario:
In each of MHD_MD5_update, MHD_SHA256_update and MHD_SHA512_256_update the fragment
#ifndef MHD_FAVOR_SMALL_CODE
  if (0 == length)
    return; /* Shortcut, do nothing */
#endif
is an early-return optimization. When it is compiled in and executed for calls with length == 0 it performs no observable action; removing the if/return does not change program behaviour because the rest of the function is safe for length == 0 (the count is unchanged, no transforms or memcpy occur). Thus the if/return is an operation that can be executed but whose removal would not affect program behaviour (dead code). This violates MISRA C 2023 Rule 2.2 unless a documented justification (deviation) for the optimization is provided.
</scenario>
